Someone is actually fixing my kitchen floor right now. And I'm just pretending to have a job and be working from home while I'm watching Too Hot to Handle.
If only I could manage to open the file. (Bloody OneDrive.)
I'm in.
And that's exactly when he starts drilling super loudly. Cheers.
It feels awkwardly passive-aggressive to crank my air purifier all the way up, but I can smell the wood dust, so it would even be completely okay if it weren't a mask opponent. And do I really need to protect myself?
I'd really like to go back to bed, but I can't until he's gone.
At least I've finally finished revising Chapter 4.
Chapter 5 is long, but it's so damn terrifying. Oh yes, that's the good stuff!
I'm doing a search and replace for ... ➡️ Ellipses and there are 54 of them in this chapter.
But no, I'm sticking to it. Natural language is usually staccato, especially when one becomes emotional.
The handyman is now vacuuming up the dust. Hopefully, that means he'll be finished soon.
He's gone out to cut something (sounds like that, anyway). I've been sneaking a peek to see how far he's gotten. There's still a lot to do :(
Still 7 pages in Chapter 5. It's still my favorite chapter and it's coming along nicely – mainly font changes and very small corrections to direct speech, and I need to rephrase everything to make it a bit more concise. But I really could use a break and a cup of tea right now, but the guy is still in my kitchen.
Now he's started vacuuming up dust again. Hopefully, that's a good sign.
The kitchen guy is gone.
He told me that he had drawn up a quote for the entire floor, but the landlords were too stingy and only paid for the part next to the door that's no longer in order. Feels just as good.
The house is being ventilated, and in the kitchen, my air purifier is running, while I'm having a cup of tea in the garden!
